'''Lanford Wilson''' (April 13, 1937{{ndash}} March 24, 2011) was an American [[playwright]] who helped to advance the [[Off-Off-Broadway]] theater movement.<ref name=NYTimes1>Fox, Margalit. [http://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/25/theater/lanford-wilson-pulitzer-prize-winning-playwright-dies-at-73.html "Lanford Wilson, Pulitzer Prize-Winning Playwright, Dies at 73",]  ''The New York Times'', March 24, 2011</ref>  He received the [[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]] in 1980, was elected in 2001 to the [[Theater Hall of Fame]], and in 2004 was elected to the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]].  He was nominated for three [[Tony Awards]] and won a [[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]]. 

Wilson was raised in the Midwest by his mother but moved to California where he worked and attended college.  In California, Wilson lived with his father, who did not accept Wilson's homosexuality, and so, in 1957, he moved to Chicago, where he studied playwriting.  In 1962, he moved to New York and began to write plays for [[Off-Off-Broadway]] theatres.  His 1964 short play, ''[[The Madness of Lady Bright]]'', was his first significant success and led to further works treating gay identity and other social and romantic issues throughout the 1960s.  In 1969, he was a co-founder of [[Circle Repertory Company]], for whom he wrote many plays in the 1970s.   His 1973 play, ''[[The Hot l Baltimore]]'', was the company's first major hit with both audiences and critics; its [[Off-Broadway]] run exceeded 1,000 performances.

Wilson's ''[[Fifth of July]]'' was first produced at Circle Rep in 1978; for its [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production opeining in 1980, he received his first Tony Award nomination.  A sequel, ''[[Talley's Folly]]'' (1979 at Circle Rep.) opened first on Broadway and won him the 1980 Pulitzer Prize for Drama and received another Tony nomination. ''[[Burn This]]'' (1987) was another Broadway success.  Wilson also wrote the [[libretto|libretti]] for several 20th-century operas.  In later years, he lived mostly in [[Sag Harbor]] on [[Long Island]].

==Biography==
===Early years===
Wilson was born to Ralph Eugene and Violetta Tate Wilson in [[Lebanon, Missouri]]. After his parents' divorce, he moved with his mother to [[Springfield, Missouri]], where they lived until she remarried.  He had two half-brothers, John and Jim, and one stepsister, Judy.<ref name=NYTimes1/>  When he was 11, they moved to [[Ozark, Missouri]].<ref name=Barnett2>Barnett, p. 2</ref> There, he attended high school and developed a love for film and art.{{Citation needed|date=November 2011}} As a child, he enjoyed writing short stories and going to see plays performed at Southwest Missouri State College (now [[Missouri State University]]).<ref>Barnett, p. 1</ref> He developed an interest in acting and played roles in his high school plays, including Tom in "[[The Glass Menagerie]]" by [[Tennessee Williams]].<ref>Barnett, p. 51</ref>

After graduating from Ozark High School in 1955, Wilson began his collegiate studies at Southwest Missouri State College.<ref name=BarnettChrono>Barnett, ''Chronology''</ref> In 1956, he moved to [[San Diego, California]], where his father had relocated after his parents' divorce.<ref name=Barnett2/> He studied art and art history at San Diego State College (now [[San Diego State University]]) and also worked as a riveter in the Ryan Aircraft Plant.<ref>Barnett, pp. 2<U+2013>3</ref> His time with his father proved to be difficult, leaving Wilson feeling unwanted and unaccepted as a homosexual.{{Citation needed|date=November 2011}}  He left school and moved to Chicago in 1957, where he worked as a graphic artist for an advertising firm.<ref name=BarnettChrono/> During this time, Wilson realized that the short stories he had always enjoyed writing would be more effective as plays, and so he took playwriting at the [[University of Chicago]] extension.<ref>Barnett, p. 3</ref><ref>Jones, Chris. [http://leisureblogs.chicagotribune.com/the_theater_loop/2011/03/pulitzer-prize-winning-playwright-lanford-wilson-dead-at-73.html "Pulitzer Prize-winning Playwright Lanford Wilson Dead at 73"], ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'' March 24, 2011</ref>

===Career===
In 1962, Wilson moved to [[Greenwich Village]] in New York City.  He worked in odd jobs before finding a job in the subscriptions office of the [[New York Shakespeare Festival]].{{cn|date=November 2011}}  Wilson began his professional career as a playwright writing [[one-act play|one-act plays]] for [[Caffe Cino]], a coffeehouse and small theatre run by [[Joe Cino|Joseph Cino]], a pioneer of the [[Off-Off-Broadway]] theatre movement. <ref>[http://caffecino.wordpress.com/1939/01/01/lanford-wilson/ Caffe Cino Pictures: Lanford Wilson: The Mozart from Missouri]</ref><ref>Williams, p. 17</ref><ref>Barnett, p. 4</ref> His works for Caffe Cino include ''Ludlow Fair'', ''[[Home Free!]]'' and ''[[The Madness of Lady Bright]]''. He worked odd jobs to support himself during this Off-Off-Broadway apprenticeship.<ref>Busby, p. ?</ref>{{page?}}  ''The Madness of Lady Bright'' premiered at Caffe Cino in May 1964 and was the venue's first significant success. The play concerns Leslie Bright, a neurotic aging [[drag queen]].  It is an important early stage representation of [[homosexuality]], but Wilson stated, "If it's taken as the first homosexual play, I have a feeling that I'm not very fond of it. ...  That will pass, I think, and it'll be just the story of a lonely person."<ref>Barnett, p. 14</ref> It ran for over 200 performances,<ref name=Barnett5>Barnett, p. 5</ref> setting a record as the longest-running play at Caffe Cino.<ref>Busby, p. ?</ref>{{page?}}

[[File:Lee Taylor-Allen & Kenneth Boys.jpg|thumb|Joanna (Lee Taylor-Allan) and Lawrence (Kenneth Boys) in a scene from the 1986 New York revival of Wilson's ''[[Home Free!]]'']]
In 1965, Wilson also began writing plays for Ellen Stewart's [[La MaMa Experimental Theatre Club]].<ref name=Barnett5/>  His first full-length plays premiered there, including ''[[Balm in Gilead]]'', which depicted a doomed romance in a greasy spoon diner inhabited by junkies, prostitutes and thieves.<ref name=Barnett5></ref><ref>Barnett, p. 19</ref> It premiered at LaMaMa in 1965, directed by [[Marshall W. Mason]], and was revived [[Off-Broadway]] in 1984, directed by [[John Malkovich]], and co-produced by [[Circle Repertory Company]] and the [[Steppenwolf Theatre Company]].<ref>Busby, p. ?</ref>{{page?}}  ''[[The Rimers of Eldritch]]'' (1967), a play set in the Midwest, won the 1966<U+2013>1967 [[Drama Desk Award|Drama Desk Vernon Rice Award]] for contribution to Off-Broadway theatre.<ref>Bryer, p. ?</ref>{{page?}} This was followed by ''The Gingham Dog'' (1968) about the breakup of an interracial couple.<ref>Barnett, pp. 42<U+2013>43</ref> Wilson described ''[[Lemon Sky]]'' (1970) as "directly autobiographical"; the narrator, Alan, Wilson's representation of himself, describes an attempt to reconcile with his long-absent father.  Son and father fail to meet each other's expectations, and Alan leaves, disillusioned by his father's authoritarianism and narrow-mindedness.<ref>Barnett, p. 49</ref> 

Wilson was a co-founder of [[Circle Repertory Company]] in 1969, and many of his plays were first presented there, directed by his long-standing collaborator, [[Marshall W. Mason]].<ref>Williams, p. 25</ref><ref>Lunden, Jeff. [http://www.npr.org/2011/03/25/134855822/for-lanford-wilson-the-plays-were-always-personal "For Lanford Wilson, the Plays Were Always Personal"], www.npr.org, March 25, 2011</ref>  His first plays for the Company, ''The Great Nebula in Orion'', ''Ikke, Ikke, Nye, Nye, Nye'', and ''The Family Continues'', premiered in 1972.<ref>Williams, p. 28</ref> Wilson's ''[[The Hot l Baltimore]]'', about lowlifes who face eviction when the decaying hotel in which they live is to be demolished, opened in 1973 and was Circle Rep.'s first commercial success; it also won the [[New York Drama Critics' Circle]] Award and the [[Obie Award]].<ref name=Williams3134>Williams, pp. 31<U+2013>34</ref> It transferred to the [[Circle in the Square Theatre]], then [[Off-Broadway]], and ran for 1,166 performances.<ref name=Barnett8586>Barnett, pp. 85<U+2013>86</ref> It was adapted into a short-lived television series by [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in 1975, which Wilson pronounced "a disaster".<ref name=Williams3134/><ref name=Barnett8586/> In 1975, Wilson's ''The Mound Builders'', which ''[[The New York Times]]'' described as Wilson's "most ambitious work", premiered at Circle Rep.<ref>Barnett, p. 94</ref> Its story concerned an ill-fated archeological dig in the Midwest, and, thematically, it contemplated the futility of man's achievements.<ref>Barnett, pp. 100<U+2013>01</ref>  Circle Repertory Company produced Wilson's ''[[Serenading Louie]]'' in 1976.  The play had been unsuccessfully performed in 1970 by the Washington Theater Club, and Wilson revised it for Circle Rep.'s 1976 production, which is generally regarded as its official premiere.<ref>Barnett, p. 68</ref> Wilson was also a founding member of the [[New York State Summer School of the Arts]], of which Circle Rep was the theatre contingent.<ref>Busby, p. ?</ref>{{page?}}  

Gay [[sexual identity|identity]] is a major theme in Wilson's work.<ref>[http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118034376?categoryid=4076&cs=1&cmpid=RSS%7CNews%7CLatestNews Lanford Wilson, ''Burn This'' playwright, dies at 73"], ''Variety'', March 24, 2011</ref><ref name=NYTimes1/>''The Madness of Lady Bright'', ''Lemon Sky'', ''[[Fifth of July]]'' (1978) and ''[[Burn This]]'' (1986) all deal with sexual identity.  In ''[[Fifth of July]]'', a hit on Broadway in 1980<U+2013>82, members of the Tally family decide whether to sell the family farmhouse in Missouri; the story centers on Ken Tally, a disabled [[Vietnam War]] veteran, and his lover Jed, who are currently living in the house.<ref>Barnett, pp. 109<U+2013>10</ref>  Wilson was nominated for the [[Tony Award for Best Play]] for ''Fifth of July''.<ref name=Kennedy>{{cite web|last=Kennedy|first=Mark|title=Tony Award-Winning Playwright Lanford Wilson Dies| url= http://www.backstage.com/bso/content_display/news-and-features/e3i9343b011681a9d0d67eead562686e1c6 |work=Backstage |accessdate=March 24, 2011}}</ref> After ''Fifth of July'', Wilson wrote ''[[Talley's Folly]]'' (1979) and ''[[Talley & Son]]'', which premiered as ''A Tale Told'' in 1981 but was substantially rewritten and renamed, opening in 1985.<ref>Barnett, p. 141</ref>  Both are prequels, set 30 years prior to ''Fifth of July''.<ref>Barnett, pp. 107<U+2013>08</ref> ''[[Talley's Folly]]'' was was awarded the [[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]] in 1980 and received a nomination for the Tony Award for Best Play.<ref>Barnett, p. 118</ref>  ''[[Angels Fall]]'' was not a success on Broadway in 1983, but earned Wilson his third nomination for the Tony Award for Best Play.{{cn}}  In ''[[Burn This]]'', a central character is a gay man who writes advertising for a living and is involved with both gay and [[heterosexuality|straight]] friends, one of whom has died in a boating accident before the play begins.  The group struggles together to deal with their collective grief.  John Malkovich starred in the original production.<ref>Bryer, p. ?</ref>{{page?}}  Wilson and Mason encouraged so-called [[method acting|"method" acting]] and often used the classic techniques of [[Anton Chekhov]], updated with [[modernist]] and [[post-modernist]] touches.<ref>Bryer, p. ?</ref>{{page?}}   

In addition to writing plays, Wilson wrote the texts for several 20th-century [[opera]]s, collaborating with composer [[Lee Hoiby]] for ''Summer and Smoke'' (1971), and adapting his own play, ''This is the Rill Speaking'' (1992).<ref name=ON>[http://www.operanews.com/operanews/templates/content.aspx?id=19386 "Lee Hoiby, 85, American Opera Composer, Has Died",] ''Opera News'', March 28, 2011</ref><ref name=Kennedy/> ''Summer and Smoke'' is an adapatation of the [[Tennessee Williams]] [[Summer and Smoke|play of the same name]].  Williams gave composer Hoiby permission to compose an opera based on the play, and Hoiby asked Wilson to adapt the play into libretto form.<ref name=Barnett106>Barnett, p. 106</ref> ''This is the Rill Speaking'' is a one-act [[chamber opera]] that Wilson adapted from his own play of the same name.<ref name=ON/> 

In 2010, [[Debra Monk]] presented Wilson with the Artistic Achievement Award from the [[New York Innovative Theatre Awards]].  This honor was awarded by the Off-Off-Broadway community "in recognition of his brave and unique works that helped establish the Off-Off-Broadway community and propel the independent theatre voice as an important contributor to the American stage."<ref>Andronico, Michael. [http://www.backstage.com/bso/news-and-features-news/winners-of-2010-it-awards-announced-1004115788.story "Winners of 2010 IT Awards Announced"], ''Back Stage'', September 21, 2010</ref><ref>Bacalzo, Dan. [http://www.theatermania.com/new-york/news/09-2010/children-of-eden-samuel-and-alasdair-and-more-win_30608.html "''Children of Eden'', ''Samuel and Alasdair'', and More Win 2010 IT Awards"], Theatremania, September 20, 2010</ref>

===Personal life and death===
After Wilson moved to New York City in 1962, he settled in a small apartment in West Greenwich Village on Sheridan Square, where he lived for many years.  In the 1970s, he bought a house in [[Sag Harbor]], [[Long Island]], New York.<ref name=BarnettChrono/> He lived in both places, using his Manhattan apartment mainly when he had a play in production there.  He also became active in a community theatre company in Sag Harbor and produced some of his shorter plays there.{{Citation needed|date=November 2011}}  

When living in Manhattan, he worked with Playwrights Laboratory at the Circle Repertory Company, often attending readings, rehearsals, and productions. Around 1998, he finally gave up his apartment in New York and lived full-time in Sag Harbor. Wilson was openly homosexual and never had children. In 2004, he was elected to the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} 

On March 24, 2011, Wilson died, aged 73, from complications of pneumonia.<ref name=NYTimes1/>

